  25  """ 
  26  Pymel 
  27  ===== 
  28   
  29  Pymel makes python scripting with Maya work the way it should. Maya's command module is a direct 
  30  translation of mel commands into python commands. The result is a very awkward and unpythonic syntax which 
  31  does not take advantage of python's strengths -- particulary, a flexible object-oriented design. Pymel 
  32  builds on the maya.cmds module by organizing many of its commands into a class hierarchy, and by 
  33  customizing them to operate in a more succinct and intuitive way. 
  34   
  35  Pymel Features: 
  36          - powerful new classes for nodes, attributes, file paths, sets and vectors 
  37          - customized operators for succinct scripting 
  38          - allows mel procedures to be called as if they were python commands: no more annoying string formatting 
  39          - mel-to-python translator for converting mel script into python scripts 
  40          - python-to-mel plugin factory for turning python classes into mel commands 
  41   
  42   
  43                           
  44  take a look at this simple comparison: 
  45   
  46   
  47  MEL 
  48  --- 
  49  :: 
  50          string $objs[] = `ls -type transform`; 
  51          for ($x in $objs) { 
  52                  connectAttr( $x + ".sx") ($x + ".sy"); 
  53                  disconnectAttr( $x + ".sx") ($x + ".sy"); 
  54                  setAttr ($x + ".rotate") 1 1 1;  
  55                  string $conn[] = `listConnections -s 0 -d 1 -p 1 ($x + ".tx")`; 
  56                  for ($inputPlug in $conn) 
  57                          disconnectAttr $inputPlug ($x + ".tx"); 
  58                  move 1 2 3 $x; 
  59                  float $trans[] = `getAttr ($x + ".translate")`; 
  60                  float $scale[] = `getAttr ($x + ".scale")`; 
  61                  $trans[0] *= $scale[0]; 
  62                  $trans[1] *= $scale[1]; 
  63                  $trans[2] *= $scale[2]; 
  64                  setAttr ($x + ".scale") $trans[0] $trans[1] $trans[2]; 
  65                  myMelScript( `nodeType $x`, $trans ); 
  66                  print longNameOf($x);    
  67          } 
  68   
  69   
  70  Default Python 
  71  -------------- 
  72  :: 
  73          import maya.cmds as cmds 
  74          import maya.mel as mm 
  75          objs = cmds.ls( type= 'transform')  
  76          if objs is not None:                                                            # maya.cmds.ls returns None when it finds no matches 
  77                  for x in objs: 
  78                          cmds.connectAttr( '%s.sx' % x,  '%s.sy' % x) 
  79                          cmds.disconnectAttr( '%s.sx' % x,  '%s.sy' % x) 
  80                          cmds.setAttr ( '%s.rotate' % x, 1,  1, 1 ) 
  81                          conn = listConnections( x + ".tx", s=0, d=1, p=1) 
  82                          if conn: 
  83                                  for (inputPlug in conn) 
  84                                          disconnectAttr( inputPlug, x + ".tx")    
  85                          cmds.move( 1, 2, 3, x )                 # confusing syntax 
  86                          trans = cmds.getAttr ( '%s.translate' % x ) 
  87                          trans = trans[0]                                # maya packs the previous result list in a tuple for no apparent reason 
  88                          scale = cmds.getAttr ( '%s.sclae' % x )[0] 
  89                          trans[0] *= scale[0] 
  90                          trans[1] *= scale[1] 
  91                          trans[2] *= scale[2] 
  92                          cmds.setAttr ( '%s.scale' % x, trans[0], trans[1], trans[2] ) 
  93                          mm.eval('myMelScript("%s",{%s,%s,%s})' % (cmds.nodeType(x), trans[0], trans[1], trans[2]) 
  94                          print mm.eval('longNameOf("%s")', x) 
  95   
  96   
  97  With Pymel 
  98  ---------- 
  99  :: 
 100          from pymel import *                                             # safe to import into main namespace 
 101          for x in ls( type='transform'): 
 102                  x.sx >> s.sy                                            # connection operator 
 103                  x.sx <> s.sy                                            # disconnection operator 
 104                  x.tx.disconnect()                                       # smarter methods -- (automatically disconnects all inputs and outputs when no arg is passed) 
 105                  x._rotate.set( 1, 1, 1 )         
 106                  x.move( 1, 2, 3 ) 
 107                  trans = x._translate.get() 
 108                  trans *= x._scale.get()                         # vector math 
 109                  x._translate.set(trans)                         # ability to pass list/vector args 
 110                  mel.myMelScript( x.type(), trans)       # automatic handling of mel commands 
 111                  print x.longName()                                      # object oriented design 
 112   
 113   
 114  As you can see, pymel has a lot of little touches that make writing python code in maya a lot simpler -- as 
 115  it should be.  pymel handles automatic casting of arguments and return values as much as it can, so that 
 116  you don't have to.  for example, the 'get' method returns a simple vector type when returning triples from 
 117  transforms so you can perform vector math on the fly.  also, you can set triple values directly as a list,  
 118  instead of having to unpack it (see the scale setAttr example above). Another nice feature is that pymel  
 119  commands that return lists (such as ls and listRelatives) return empty lists instead of nothing when they  
 120  find no match.  that is why, in the above examples, the default python example must first place the 'ls' 
 121  results in a variable and check if it is 'None', whereas the pymel example will simply not enter the for loop 
 122  if there are no transforms in the scene.  
 123   
 124   
 125  Mel Scripts 
 126  =========== 
 127  calling mel scripts through maya.mel.eval is a nuisances because it requires so much string formatting on  
 128  the programmer's part.  pymel.mel handles all of that for you so you can use your mel scripts as if they  
 129  were python functions. this includes automatically formatting all iterable types into maya arrays. 
 130   
 131   
 132  Module Namespaces 
 133  ================= 
 134   
 135  another problem is that importing maya.cmds into the root namespace (e.g. 'from maya.cmds import *') 
 136  is dangerous because it will override several of python's more important built-in methods. pymel is designed 
 137  to be safe to import into the root namespace so that scripts can be written much more concisely. All the maya.cmds  
 138  methods are in pymel, except the conflicting ones ( file, filter, eval, help, and quit) which can be found 
 139  in the pymel.cmds namespace.  All of the file command's functionality can still be found directly within the pymel 
 140  namespace where the file command has been broken down into multiple functions -- one for each primary flag -- 
 141  each inheriting all of the same sub-flags and default values.   
 142   
 143  instead of this: 
 144           
 145          >>> cmds.file( exportAll=1, preserveReferences=1 ) 
 146           
 147  you can do this: 
 148   
 149          >>> exportAll( preserveReferences=1) 
 150           
 151   
 152   
 153   
 154  Class Hiearchy 
 155  ============== 
 156   
 157  the pymel module organizes the myriad mel commands into a a hierarchy of classes, and provides many  
 158  additional helper methods. This design allows you to write much more concise and readable python code,  
 159  surpassing even mel in many cases.  
 160   
 161          - str 
 162                  - _BaseObj 
 163                          - Attribute 
 164                          - Node 
 165                                  - Dag 
 166                                          - Transform 
 167                                          - Poly 
 168                                          - Nurbs 
 169                                          - Curve 
 170   
 171  the _BaseObj is a subclass of python's built-in string, which allows it to be easily printed, passed to  
 172  unwrapped commands and used as a key in dictionaries. however, since it is immutable, when calling  
 173  commands like 'rename', the calling instance will point to an invalid object after the rename, so you  
 174  need to assign the result of the command to a new instance. also, attributes that refer to the renamed  
 175  objects will become invalid. for example: 
 176   
 177          >>> orig = Poly('pSphere1') 
 178          >>> new = orig.rename('crazySphere') 
 179          >>> print orig.exists(), new.exists() 
 180          (0, 1) # 
 181   
 182   
 183  Objects 
 184  ======= 
 185   
 186  in order to use the object-oriented design of pymel, you must ensure that the objects that you are working  
 187  with are instances of pymel classes. to make this easier, this module contains wrapped version  
 188  of the more common commands for getting lists of objects: ls, listRelatives, and various creation commands  
 189  such as polySphere, createNode, among many others. these methods attempt to cast their results to the appropriate  
 190  class type (check the code below under the headings 'Commands for Returning pymel objects' and 'Commands  
 191  for Creating pymel objects'). maya's versions of these commands return unicode strings, which can be used to  
 192  initialize a pymel class.  for example: 
 193   
 194   
 195  you can convert from a string to a pymel class --- 
 196          >>> s = cmds.polySphere()[0] 
 197          >>> type(s) 
 198          <type 'unicode'> #  
 199          >>>      
 200          >>> s = Poly(s)  
 201          >>> type(s) 
 202          <class 'pymel.Poly'> #  
 203           
 204  or you can just use the pymel version of the command 
 205          >>> t = polySphere()[0] 
 206          >>> type(t) 
 207          <class 'pymel.Poly'> #  
 208   
 209  to make life even simpler, there is a 'scene' keyword which allows you to quickly wrap your objects into pymel types. 
 210           
 211  for instance, instead of this: 
 212          >>> Transform('pSphere2').ty.get() 
 213           
 214  you can do this: 
 215          >>> scene.pSphere2.ty.get()

 218  Setup 
 219  ===== 
 220   
 221  if you have not done so already, it is a good idea to setup a directory for your published python scripts so that 
 222  they will be accessible from within maya.  you do this by setting the PYTHONPATH environment variable in Maya.env.   
 223  if you want to use your current maya scripts directory simply add this to your Maya.env: 
 224   
 225  PYTHONPATH = $MAYA_SCRIPT_PATH 
 226   
 227  then place the pymel directory in your PYTHONPATH directory. 
 228   
 229  next, to avoid having to import pymel every time you startup, if you have not done so already, you can create a userSetup.mel 
 230  file, place it in your scipts directory and add this line: 
 231   
 232  python("from pymel import *");   
 233   
 234  Note, that if you are running a linux/unix variant, including osx, and you have your PYTHONPATH set in a shell resource file,  
 235  this value will override your Maya.env value if you launch maya from the terminal.soyou
